<TITLE> Falklands oil row reaches UN </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 UN, Feb 25 (bdnews24.com/Reuters)--- Argentine Foreign Minister Jorge Taiana meets with United Nations Secretary Ban Ki-moon over row on oil exploration in the disputed Falkland Islands. The oil well drilling dispute between Britain and Argentina reached the United Nations on Wednesday. Argentina's foreign minister, Jorge Taiana, met with UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon and afterwards said that the drilling contravenes Security Council resolutions. Jorge Taiana, Foreign Minister of Argentina, saying (Spanish): "This is a unilateral act in a series of unilateral acts that the United Kingdom has realized. It is an act that we consider clearly illegal, contrary to the international law and contrary to clear United Nations resolutions." The UN says it is available for mediation if both parties request it. Britain says there is nothing to discuss. But Argentina is challenging British company Desire Petroleum's drilling and Taiana insists that his country will do everything in its power to stop it. Jorge Taiana, Foreign Minister of Argentina, saying (Spanish): "We will defend the rights and resources of the Argentine people through all diplomatic means availble to us and our rights within international law." Argentina invaded the British ruled Falkland Islands in 1982, attempting to regain control. It was forced to withdraw, but still claims the archipel
